        <h1>Grade 4 Unit 4 Informational Common Assessment</h1>

        <h2>Standards</h2>
        <p><strong>RI.4.2:</strong> Determine the main idea of a text and explain how it is supported by key details; summarize the text.</p>
        <p><strong>RI.4.5:</strong> Describe the overall structure (e.g., chronology, comparison, cause/effect, problem/solution) of events, ideas, concepts, or information in a text or part of a text.</p>

        <h2>Directions</h2>
        <p>Read the text and answer the questions below.</p>

        <h2>Illinois: The Prairie State</h2>
        <p><strong>By National Geographic Partners, adapted by Newsela staff</strong></p>

        <p><strong>1.</strong> Archaeologists aren't sure exactly when the first people arrived in what's now Illinois...</p>
        <p><strong>2.</strong> The first Europeans to reach the area were French explorers Jacques Marquette and Louis Jolliet...</p>
        <p><strong>3.</strong> After the American Revolution, Illinois became a U.S. territory...</p>
        <p><strong>4.</strong> Disaster struck in 1871, when a huge fire swept through Chicago, Illinois...</p>

        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1a/Map_of_USA_IL.svg" alt="Map of the United States with Illinois highlighted" style="display: block; margin: auto; width: 80%;">

        <p><strong>5.</strong> The name Illinois comes from the Native American tribe that lived there...</p>
        <p><strong>6.</strong> Black bears, bobcats, and white-tailed deer are a few of this state's common mammals...</p>
        <p><strong>7.</strong> One of Illinois's best-known natural resources is its rich soil...</p>
        <p><strong>8.</strong> The state's official snack food is popcorn...</p>
        <p><strong>9.</strong> Illinois is known as the Land of Lincoln...</p>

